<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="881" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="69.[160,1155,558,617]" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,292,558,582]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named ‘pygmaeus’ because of the small size of the wasp. The name is treated as an adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="881" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="69.[160,1156,662,860]" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,283,662,686]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is closer to 
<taxonomicName authority="Kamalanathan &amp; Mohanraj &amp; Samuel &amp; Reddy, 2020" authorityName="Kamalanathan &amp; Mohanraj &amp; Samuel &amp; Reddy" authorityYear="2020" box="[561,666,663,687]" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Baeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="881" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[561,666,663,687]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">B. striatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[672,730,663,687]" pageId="69" pageNumber="881" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
In 
<taxonomicName authority="Kamalanathan &amp; Mohanraj &amp; Samuel &amp; Reddy, 2020" authorityName="Kamalanathan &amp; Mohanraj &amp; Samuel &amp; Reddy" authorityYear="2020" box="[763,900,663,687]" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Baeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="881" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygmaeus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[763,900,663,687]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">B. pygmaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[906,964,663,687]" pageId="69" pageNumber="881" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
posterior ocellus is closer to hyperoccipital carina, genal suture sinuate, metasoma smooth and carinae of dorsal mesopleuron extend below the dorsal level of metapleuron. Whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Kamalanathan &amp; Mohanraj &amp; Samuel &amp; Reddy, 2020" authorityName="Kamalanathan &amp; Mohanraj &amp; Samuel &amp; Reddy" authorityYear="2020" box="[1050,1155,732,756]" class="Insecta" family="Scelionidae" genus="Baeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="881" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="striatus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1050,1155,732,756]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="881">B. striatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[160,223,767,791]" pageId="69" pageNumber="881" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
posterior ocellus away from hyperoccipital carina, genal suture almost straight, metasoma reticulate and carinae of dorsal mesopleuron terminate above the level of dorsal metapleuron.
</paragraph>
